    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="summary">
                <p>
                    The Hogarth Press give permission to <abbr>A.R.</abbr><expan>Arthur Reginald</expan>Moon, Esq. to quote a passage from The Edwardians in an English textbook.
                    They request that he give credit to the author and publisher.
                </p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>

                    <address>
                        <addrLine>
                        <persName key="MAPP0003">A. R. Moon, Esq.,</persName>
                        </addrLine>
                            <addrLine>46, Redhill Drive,</addrLine>
                            <addrLine>EDGWARE.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1937-04-20">20th April, 1937</date>:
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>
                        Dear Sir,
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                  We thank you for your letter of <lb/>
                  April 17th, and are pleased to give you permission <lb/>
                  to quote the sentence you mention from <title>THE <lb/>
                  EDWARDIANS</title> in your forthcoming text-book on English. <lb/>
                  We shall be grateful if you will <lb/>
                  make due acknowledgments to <persName key="Q235505">the author{Vita Sackville-West}</persName> and to our-<lb/>
                  selves as publishers, as you suggest.
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        Yours faithfully,
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <orgName key="Q1623362">
                          THE HOGARTH PRESS
                        </orgName>
                        MANAGER. <note>According to the Modernist Archives Publishing Project, the manager at this time was a woman named Dorothy Lange (not to be confused with photographer Dorothea Lange) </note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
